@startuml
title SELinux type enforcement — access decided by labels, not UID

skinparam shadowing false
skinparam rectangle {
  BackgroundColor #f5f5f5
}

rectangle "Executable\n/bin/passwd\ntype: passwd_exec_t" as exec
rectangle "Subject (process domain)\npasswd_t" as subj
rectangle "Object\n/etc/shadow\ntype: shadow_t" as obj

rectangle "Policy rule\nallow passwd_t shadow_t:file { read write };" as rule

exec --> subj : exec triggers a\ndomain transition\nto passwd_t
subj --> rule : request read/write
rule --> obj : permitted because a\nmatching allow rule exists

note bottom of rule
  Label format on every subject/object:
  user:role:type:range
  e.g. system_u:object_r:etc_t:s0

  With no matching allow rule the access
  is refused even for root. Type
  enforcement, derived from MULTICS MLS.
end note
@enduml
